Those didn't work either. To the best of my knowledge, NES and FC Arkanoid controllers encode the data slightly differently.

```Famicom:

$4016:
7  bit  0
---- ----
xxxx xxBx
       |
       +-- Fire button (1: pressed)

$4017:
7  bit  0
---- ----
xxxx xxDx
       |
       +-- Serial control knob data (9-bit, inverted, MSb first)

NES:

7  bit  0
---- ----
xxxD Bxxx
   | |
   | +---- Fire button (1: pressed)
   +------ Serial control knob data (9-bit, inverted, MSb first)
```
4016 = port 1, 4017 = port2. Bit 1 there is sometime called D1. for NES they are talking about 4017(port2) D3,D4(bits 3,4 there)
that build D0 for port 1 isn't shared with D1. D0 is just set to 0 so fire probably won't make all the buttons light up in that test rom.

messages.content: Hey don’t know where to post this, but just want to ask why a lot of cores have had unstable nightlies or test builds for the past year or so w/out having an official release. Not counting Saturn and CD-I, I’m thinking more along the lines of the NES, Intellivision, and SNES have had major updates but the official cores haven’t been updated. Is there a reason why? I’ve heard it’s because of compatibility issues with the 3rd party boards. Is that correct?

Nah, all the boards run them fine. I wonder if it’s a mixture of not enough testing being done, and if folks just haven’t pushed the button yet.

SNES I think is being held because SRG is still working on a bug that’s in the unstable? I can’t remember for sure tho

Thx. The NES unstable added cycle accurate FDS reading speeds, and save states for FDS, the Intellivision core added fixes for Donkey Kong and Nova Blast being fixed. The SNES core still has save states being a WIP though, but I think NES and Intellivision need a new stable release for sure
There’s a lot of TG16 fixes too, but I haven’t messed around with it

Tg16 is definitely in active development right now. The unstables introduced regressions, which is why they weren’t pushed. 

I can’t comment on NES or intellivision tho.

@Grabulosaure hey I tested your test build for Intellivision from a while ago and it does indeed fix the issues present in Donkey Kong where the hammer wasn’t able to be picked up as well as the freezing issues in Nova Blast. Thanks for fixing these two issues. Do you plan on adding it to update_all?

Yeah the Intellivision test build was just one build from a while ago, but there’s a bunch of new fixes on the NES core by paulbnl. The FDS fixes are pretty important though because it added the ability to save your game, cycle accurate disk loading and save states. The FDS is essentially feature complete now so I want everyone to be able to experience it as long as there’s no regressions
@KremlingKuthroat19 Yeah, I should push the latest build. I wanted to add a CFG file parser to support more ROM files formats, but it is still not finished yet.
Thanks! Yeah whenever you're ready. I was just hoping that the Intellivision core wasn't forgotten given the updates were pretty big in the latest couple of test builds

The problem on INTV is that supporting some weird ROMs and homebrews need to use SDRAM instead of just FPGA RAM, have a way to parse CFG text files... so it's not trivial for a small number of games probably mostly played on the JZINTV emulator.

If there is a hard cut off beyond 15.3khz, as in a very steep filter, the Mister won't be able to replicate it. Right now the Mister can use 3rd order LPFs at most, which wouldn't be nearly sufficient to re-create such a hard cutoff. You'll also not be able to approximate such scenario with any of the generic filter presets, which if I recall correctly mostly use 1st and 2nd order LPFs.

In terms of my current audio work I'm at a position where I'm stuck and can't progress.

The current IIR audio filter is very unpredictable in how it works and is very difficult to work with if highly accurate results are wanted. For example to develop the N64 filter I had to create roughly 300-400 different filter presets and manually compare them against the target frequency response to find the best possible match.

Additionally many of the filter presets end up completely bugging out the entire audio output, making the situation even more difficult to work with, or in some cases entirely impossible.

Lastly I discovered an issue with noticeable aliasing distortion being produced, likely happening at the stage where the core audio output signal is re-sampled for the intended audio output sample rate, where high frequencies are not correctly filtered and therefore being mirrored back as distortion artefacts.

This has likely also invalidated my own methods of testing and developing audio filters, which is why I decided not to release any of my work at this point, until these issues can be solved.

The aliasing distortion issue is also directly related to the issue that you previously spoke about with the Genesis or MegaDrive core requiring a very noticeable audio filter built directly into the core to deal with the symptoms of this issue, which in turn also prevents it from sounding like the real console.

I have chatted with FPGAzumSpass about these issues for a while now, as well as possible solutions, however I don't know when we'll be able to dig deeper into finding solutions for these issues.

My newest plan or project is to create an archival grade resource of uncompressed media across all PAL & NTSC console systems and all natively supported signal types, such as various audio test tones as well as recordings of image calibration screens, game menues and attract modes. The reasons to create such resource is to have extremely accurate resouces to work with to allow re-creating the signal level effects of the various console output signals, such as for example PS1 composite output including having correct color reproduction, horizontal blend, vertical blend and audio frequency response, and to draw more attention to this topic in general.

In any case, another thing that tends to be important here is to understand at what point a signal changes, or what aspect is dependent on what portion of the circuit.  When you're modelling a complex system, it's important to understand the characteristics of each component, in order to understand hos they can possibly interact - instead of just trying to create a "composite sum" result.
So I come back to, what does thte raw audio look like

I'm not sure if it's of any benefit though, other than gaining more detailed information and knowledge, as it can be incredibly complex to create such component modeling circuit in digital form, and having it potentially require lots of processing resources in addition.

There are plenty of software companies doing just that in the music industry, with all sorts of audio equipment such as preamps, equalizers and full recording consoles emulated using this specific approach, and in the end the results always fall short of the target systems. They don't end up sounding the same, but like a lesser versions of the target systems or devices which they aim to digitally re-create or emulate.

In my opinion getting to understand the frequency response of the target system and the Mister by analyzing their outputs directly, and applying the differential equalization curve, preferably using a high quality FIR filter, will yield much better results, at much lower processing resources requirements, with only a few parameters to adjust vs theoretically a few hundred parameters. Of course this only applies to the filtering of the entire signal, already assuming that the core developer would take care of any filtering that happens to individual sound channels internally.

No, that's not at all what I'm talking about.  If the artifact is not there in direct audio output, but is there only as a result of the RF modulator, then you can AT LEAST tune the "REAL" audio response curve via MDFourier, and add a RF modulator on the output.  As mentioned previously, RF was only one possible output, and there is almost certainly significant variance among units for that.
But if you can't get the most basic response curve correct, it will always sound wrong, even if you can somehow model that RF modulator (which I would caution against in the first place)

If you try instead to model the AGGREGATE of all possible distortions, degradations, and filters - both intentional and unintentional - at once, it is trying to solve a multivariate equation in multiple unknowns with mere guesswork.  It's simply not the right set of tools.

Thanks for the clarification. I can't comment much on RF as I know nothing about it, but what you describe makes sense.

From my own findings the most important aspects when it comes to adjusting the audio output are frequency response and phase response, at least in the case of the N64's composite output. Having adjusted these two aspects made the sound almost identical to the actual console, disregarding the issue of the aliasing distortion.

The questions then become, which aspects do we care about re-creating, what does it take to re-create these aspects, and what is possible to be re-created with the Mister?
